<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1887-10-15T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1887-10-15T00:00:00-05:00" n="483" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d483">
                        <head>No. 28.<lb/><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Garland</persName> to Mr. <persName type="to">Bayard</persName></hi>.</head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of Justice</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1887-10-15"><hi rend="italic">October</hi> 15,
                                1887</date>. (Received.October 17.)</dateline></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to say, in reply to your
                            letter of the 13th instant, in relation to the release of the vessels
                                <hi rend="italic">Carolena, Onward</hi>, and <hi rend="italic">Thornton</hi>, that before your request was received I had repeated
                            the instructions <pb facs="0840" n="1798" xml:id="pg_1798"/> by
                            telegraph to the marshal for Alaska, and since its receipt have, as you
                            suggested, supplemented the telegram by a letter, both of these
                            communications directing that the instructions of January last be
                            carried out.</p>
                        <p>Very respectfully,</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">A. H. Garland.</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>